<paragraph blockId="6.[168,778,1755,2091]" pageId="6" pageNumber="883">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[168,330,1933,1957]" pageId="6" pageNumber="883">Identification.</emphasis>
This species differs from other bats in having two whitish longitudinal wavy stripes on the dorsum. Besides, the individuals had the underparts brownish; the muzzle was simple, pointed, and without a leaf-like excrescence; the uropatagium was thinly
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[808,1422,888,1285]" pageId="6" pageNumber="883">
haired to the exertion of the tail; and the tail perforated the upper surface of the uropatagium. These morphological characters agree with those described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hall ER" box="[1296,1416,955,979]" pageId="6" pageNumber="883" pagination="601 - 1181" refId="ref10203" refString="Hall ER (1981) The mammals of North America. Second edition. John Wiley and Sons, New York, 1: xv + 1 - 600 + 90 pp.; 2: vi + 601 - 1181 + 90 pp." type="book chapter" year="1981">Hall (1981)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Yancey FD &amp; Goetze JR &amp; Jones C" box="[809,1024,988,1013]" pageId="6" pageNumber="883" pagination="1 - 5" refId="ref14099" refString="Yancey FD, Goetze JR, Jones C (1998) Saccopteryx bilineata. Mammalian Species 581: 1 - 5. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 3504459" type="journal article" year="1998">Yancey et al. (1998)</bibRefCitation>
, and 
<bibRefCitation author="Diaz MM &amp; Solari S &amp; Aguirre LF &amp; Aguiar LMS &amp; Barquez RM" box="[1080,1266,988,1012]" pageId="6" pageNumber="883" refId="ref9508" refString="Diaz MM, Solari S, Aguirre LF, Aguiar LMS, Barquez RM (2016) Clave de identificacion de los murcielagos de Sud America. Pub- licacion especial N ° 2, PCMA (Programa de Conservacion de los Murcielagos de Argentina), Tucuman, Argentina, 160 pp." type="book" year="2016">Díaz et al. (2016)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="883" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[808,1422,888,1285]" pageId="6" pageNumber="883">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[810,921,1027,1051]" pageId="6" pageNumber="883">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species occurs from 
<collectingCountry box="[1201,1309,1027,1051]" name="Colombia" pageId="6" pageNumber="883">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1319,1416,1027,1051]" name="Trinidad and Tobago" pageId="6" pageNumber="883">Trinidad</collectingCountry>
, and the Guianas to 
<collectingCountry box="[1012,1091,1060,1084]" name="Bolivia" pageId="6" pageNumber="883">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1140,1207,1060,1084]" name="Brazil" pageId="6" pageNumber="883">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(Hood and Gardner 2008). In 
<collectingCountry box="[913,966,1094,1117]" name="Peru" pageId="6" pageNumber="883">Peru</collectingCountry>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1838" box="[979,1102,1094,1118]" class="Mammalia" family="Emballonuridae" genus="Saccopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="883" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bilineata">
<emphasis box="[979,1102,1094,1118]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="883">S. bilineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in the Bosque Pluvial del Pacífico, Selva Baja, and Sabana de Palmera ecore- gions (
<bibRefCitation author="Pacheco V &amp; Cadenillas R &amp; Salas E &amp; Tello C &amp; Zeballos H" box="[883,1101,1161,1185]" pageId="6" pageNumber="883" pagination="5 - 32" refId="ref12058" refString="Pacheco V, Cadenillas R, Salas E, Tello C, Zeballos H (2009) Diversidad y endemismo de los mamiferos del Peru. Revista Peruana de Biologia 16: 5 - 32. https: // doi. org / 10.15381 / rpb. v 16 i 1.111" type="journal article" year="2009">Pacheco et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
). The new record in the eastern Andes of 
<collectingCountry box="[961,1011,1195,1218]" name="Peru" pageId="6" pageNumber="883">Peru</collectingCountry>
extends the range of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1838" box="[1248,1372,1194,1218]" class="Mammalia" family="Emballonuridae" genus="Saccopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="883" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bilineata">
<emphasis box="[1248,1372,1194,1218]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="883">S. bilineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<quantity metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.3" pageId="6" pageNumber="883" unit="km" value="430.0">430 km</quantity>
north from the nearest presious record at San Juan, 
<collectingRegion box="[812,875,1262,1285]" country="Peru" name="Pasco" pageId="6" pageNumber="883">Pasco</collectingRegion>
department (
<bibRefCitation author="Tuttle MD" box="[1016,1140,1261,1285]" pageId="6" pageNumber="883" pagination="45 - 86" refId="ref13581" refString="Tuttle MD (1970) Distribution and zoogeography of Peruvian bats, with comments on natural history. The University of Kansas Science Bulletin 49: 45 - 86. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 9197" type="journal article" year="1970">Tuttle 1970</bibRefCitation>
; Hood and Gardner 2008).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
